**Stale readiness check after spec update**

After `c.Update()` succeeds on line 43, `IsDeploymentReady(existing)` on line 47 is called on an object whose `Status` was fetched from the API server *before* the spec change (line 27). For the replica-count-unchanged case (e.g., an image-only rollout), `existing.Status.ReadyReplicas == desired` and `existing.Status.Conditions` still show `Available=True` from the pre-update state, so the function returns `true` even though the rollout has not yet started.

A robust fix is to re-fetch the object after the update:

```go
existing.Spec = deploy.Spec
if err := c.Update(ctx, existing); err != nil {
    return false, fmt.Errorf("updating Deployment %s/%s: %w", deploy.Namespace, deploy.Name, err)
}
// Re-fetch to get the server-assigned Generation after the update.
if err := c.Get(ctx, client.ObjectKeyFromObject(deploy), existing); err != nil {
    return false, fmt.Errorf("re-fetching Deployment %s/%s after update: %w", deploy.Namespace, deploy.Name, err)
}
return IsDeploymentReady(existing), nil
```

And extend `IsDeploymentReady` to guard on `ObservedGeneration`:

```go
if deploy.Status.ObservedGeneration < deploy.Generation {
    return false
}
```

The same stale-status issue affects `EnsureDatabase` (`database.go` lines 45–50), `ensureUser` (lines 94–99), `ensureGrant` (lines 119–124), and `EnsureCertificate` (`tls/tls.go` lines 44–49).

